result.execSummary:
The defendant James D Eckdahl Jr was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Fail/Report to County Jail (<10 Days), a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.425(1m)(a).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: 3:02 Defendant James D Eckdahl in court with attorney Andrew Martin Nelson.  Sean Edward Froelich appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Froelich: files an amended information charging misdemeanor report for jail. Guilty to amended charge and time served. Nelson and Def agree.   Plea Questionnaire and Waiver of Rights form is filed with the court; court reviews with Def. Def pleas guilty to amended misdemeanor charge of failure to report for jail; Nelson stipulates to factual basis.   COURT ACCEPTS PLEA, FINDS DEF FREELY, INTELLIGENTLY, KNOWINGLY & UNDERSTANDINGLY MADE AND WAIVES CONSTITUTIONAL RIGHTS. Court finds and adjudicates Def guilty of amended charge contained in amended information. Froelich and Nelson address sentencing.  Court sentences Def to time served.
Plea hearing on December 16, 2014 at 02:00 pm.

Pre-trial conference on October 28, 2014 at 11:30 am.
Def pleas not guilty to charge. Court; enters in not guilty plea. Court goes over bond conditions with Def.  Def to remain until he is handed a notice of next hearing.

2:35 Defendant James D Eckdahl in court with attorney Joshua Hargrove.  Sean Edward Froelich appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Court goes over Preliminary Questionnaire and Waiver Form with Def.   Constitutional rights explained to defendant. Exam'd re: understanding of law, penalty and rights. Def voluntary waives his right to have a preliminary hearing. Court approves the waiver. Finds the Def probably committed a felony and binds the Def over for trial. Froelich files information. Court reads charging portion of document. Def waives further reading.
Preliminary hearing on September 30, 2014 at 01:30 pm.
